140","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Home, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Home, Berwickshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hume","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Lowlands) and northern English: variant of   Hulme  , with loss of <i>l</i> before the bilabial consonant /m/, as in the vocabulary word <i>calm</i>. See   Holm   and   Home  .","Scottish: habitational name either from the barony of Home or from Hume (or Home) in Berwickshire, from which the barony took its name. The placename derives from Old English <i>hōum</i>, dative plural form of <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’.","History: A family of this name (see 2 above) have held the Earldom of Home since 1605."],"variants":[{"name":"Humes","meanings":["English (Durham): variant of   Hume  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>, or a variant of   Holmes  ."]},{"name":"Hulme","meanings":["English: variant of   Holm   and of   Home   3 and 4."]},{"name":"Home","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Hume  .","English: variant of   Holm  .","English: habitational name from Home in Clifton on Teme or in Feckenham (Worcestershire) or from a minor place similarly named, a variant of   Hamm   (from Middle English <i>ham(me)</i>, with rounding of the vowel before the nasal consonant to give <i>hom(me)</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Patrick","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Name of the apostle and patron saint of Ireland (  <i>c.</i>389–461 ), Gaelic <i>Pádraig</i>. He was a Christian Briton and a Roman citizen, who as a young man was captured and enslaved by raiders from Ireland. He escaped and went to Gaul before returning home to Britain. In about  419  he felt a call to do missionary work in Ireland. He studied for twelve years at Auxerre, and in  432  returned to Ireland. For the rest of his life it is difficult to distinguish fact from fiction. He apparently went to the court of the high kings at Tara and made some converts there; then he travelled around Ireland making further converts until about  445 , when he established his archiepiscopal see at Armagh. By the time of his death almost the whole of Ireland is said to have been converted to Christianity. He is also credited with codifying the laws of Ireland. In his Latin autobiography, as well as in later tradition, his name appears as <i>Patricius</i> ‘patrician’ (i.e. belonging to the Roman senatorial or noble class), but this may actually represent a Latinized form of some lost Celtic (British) name. In Ireland in particular, it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Patrick Hume I was born in 1140, in Berwickshire, Scotland. He married Cecilia de Fraser. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1140–":"1140–Surnud","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","1170–1248":"1170–1248","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1248":"1248","1140":"1140","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Home, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Home, Berwickshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1140–":"1140–Kuollut","1150–Female":"1150–Kuollut","1170–1248":"1170–1248","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1248":"1248","1140":"1140","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Home, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Home, Berwickshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1140–":"1140–Décédé","1150–Female":"1150–Décédée","1170–1248":"1170–1248","1140–Male":"1140–Décédé","1248":"1248","1140":"1140","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Home, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Home, Berwickshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Patrick Hume I est né en 1140, à Berwickshire, Écosse. Il a épousé Cecilia de Fraser. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé à 